{
  "doc_id": "25451",
  "text": "Additionally, this S. pyogenes lineage comprised emm89-type strains and carried a mutation in covS gene. This group produces many surface-bound and extracellular virulence factors that contribute to pathogenesis in complex ways. CovS/CovR is a key two-component regulatory system of gene transcription in S. pyogenes [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . CovS/CovR regulates the expression of 15% of the genes of S. pyogenes [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , including streptococcal pyrogenic exotoxin B (SpeB). Because the expression of active SpeB causes the degradation of secreted GAS (group A streptococci) proteins, including several virulence factors, reduced SpeB expression in covS mutants confers strong virulence on S. pyogenes [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Recent studies have also described an inverse relationship between disease severity and the degree of a cysteine protease, SpeB [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . Moreover, a previous report has suggested that mutated covS plays important roles in the in vivo dissemination of S. pyogenes in humans from the upper respiratory tract to aseptic tissues, such as blood and cerebrospinal fluid [CITATION_10] , and some studies have described the significance of covS mutations in the pathogenesis of STSS [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . In this case, it was considered that this covS mutation contributed to the development of peritonitis in a previously healthy patient.",
